08796nam a22011655i 9780824876104DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20182018hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248761047 a10.1515/97808248761042doi  a(DE-B1597)513299  a(OCoLC)1035947429  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aB5234.L4874 7aREL0180002bisacsh04a181/.11222300aLi Zehou and Confucian Philosophy /ced. by Roger T. Ames, Roger T. Ames, Peter D. Hershock, Jinhua Jia. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (408 p.) :b7 diagrams  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aConfucian Cultures00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tSeries Editors’ Preface -- tIntroduction -- tResponse to Paul Gauguin’s Triple Question -- tPart I. Li Zehou and the Modernization of Confucianism -- t1. Li Zehou and New Confucianism: A Philosophy for New Global Cultures -- t2. “Western Learning as Substance, Chinese Learning for Application”: Li Zehou’s Thought on Tradition and Modernity -- t3. Modernizing Confucianism: Li Zehou’s Vision and Inspiration for an Unfinished Project -- t4. Determinism and the Problem of Individual Freedom in Li Zehou’s Thought -- t5. What Should the World Look Like? Li Zehou, Confucius, Kant, and the World Observer -- tPart II. Li Zehou’s Reconception of Confucian Philosophy -- t6. Li Zehou’s Lunyu jindu (Reading the Analects Today) -- t7. Li Zehou’s Reconception of Confucian Ethics of Emotion -- t8. Li Zehou’s Doctrine of Emotion as Substance and Confucian Philosophy -- t9. Li Zehou and Pragmatism -- t10. Li Zehou’s View of Pragmatic Reason -- tPart III. Li Zehou’s Aesthetical Theory and Confucianism -- t11. Li Zehou’s Aesthetics: Moving On after Kant, Marx, and Confucianism -- t12. Li Zehou, Kant, and Darwin: The Theory of Sedimentation -- t13. Li Zehou’s Aesthetics and the Confucian “Body” of Chinese Cultural Sedimentation: An Inquiry into Alternative Interpretations of Confucianism -- t14. Modern Chinese Aesthetics and Its Traditional Backgrounds: A Critical Comparison of Li Zehou’s Sedimentation and Jung’s Archetypes -- t15. Li Zehou’s Aesthetics as a Form of Cognition -- tAppendix: Li Zehou’s Life and Works -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor more than a century scholars both inside and outside of China have undertaken the project of modernizing Confucianism, but few have been as successful or influential as Li Zehou (b. 1930). Since the 1950s, Li’s extensive efforts in this regard have in turn exerted a profound influence on Chinese modernization and resulted in his becoming one of China’s most prominent social critics. To transform Confucianism into a contemporary resource for positive change in China and elsewhere, Li has reinterpreted major ideas and concepts of classical Confucianism, including a rereading of the entire Analects, replete with his own philosophical speculations derived from other Chinese and Western traditions (most notably, the ideas of Kant and Marx), and developed an aesthetical theory that has proved especially far-reaching. Although the authors of this volume hail from East Asia, North America, and Europe and a wide variety of academic backgrounds and fields of study, they are unanimous in their appreciation of Li’s contributions to not only an evolving Confucian philosophy, but also world philosophy. They view Li first and foremost as a sui generis thinker with broad global interests and not one who fits neatly into any one philosophical category, Chinese or Western. This is clearly reflected in the chapters included here, which are organized into three parts: Li Zehou and the Modernization of Confucianism, Li Zehou’s Reconception of Confucian Philosophy, and Li Zehou’s Aesthetical Theory and Confucianism. Together they form a coherent narrative that reveals how Li has, for more than half a century, creatively studied, absorbed, and reconceptualized the Confucian ideational tradition to integrate it with Western philosophical elements and develop his own philosophical insights and original theories. At the same time, he has transformed and modernized Confucianism for the purpose of both coalescing with and reconstructing a new world cultural order.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aNeo-ConfucianismvCongresses. 0aPhilosophy, ConfucianvCongresses. 7aRELIGION / Confucianism.2bisacsh1 aAmes, Roger T.1 aAmes, Roger T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmes, Roger T., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBanka, Rafal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBanka, Rafal.1 aChandler, Marthe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChandler, Marthe.1 aGarrison, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarrison, James.1 aGu, Ming Dong, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGu, Ming Dong.1 aHershock, Peter D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHershock, Peter D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHuang, Chenxi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuang, Chenxi.1 aIshii, Tsuyoshi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIshii, Tsuyoshi.1 aJia, Jinhua, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJia, Jinhua, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJia, Jinhua.1 aJung, Byung-Seok.1 aJung, Byung-seok, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLambert, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel